        <div class="to-question">How can I ensure I am hosting a secure Zoom meeting?</div>
     <ul>
           <li>Microsoft Teams should be used whenever possible for remote meetings. This platform is stable and secure, and it is the best option for online meetings. If you must use zoom, please adhere to these best practices:  
             <ul>  <li>	Do not use Facebook or Gmail to sign in -- this is a poor security practice and dramatically increases the amount of personal data Zoom has access to.</li> 
                   <li>	Keep your Zoom app up to date</li>
                   <li>	Create Waiting Rooms for attendees -- You can choose to send all participants or only guests to the Waiting Room when they join your meeting (participants who are not on your Zoom account). You can then admit attendees one by one or all at once.</li>
                   <li>	Require a password for participants joining by phone -- To ensure only authorized participants join the meeting, a numeric password will be required for users joining by phone.</li>
                   <li>	Avoid using their Zoom Personal Meeting ID (PMI) to host events -- Your PMI is effectively one continuous meeting; avoid using this method to stop random crashing of your virtual space after meetings have ended.</li>
                   <li>	Only allow individuals with a given email domain to join -- As an alternative to passwords, the meeting host can only allow specific users to join the meeting.</li>
             </ul>
           </li>
      </ul>
