        <div class="to-question"> How do I ensure our patients’ protected health information (PHI) stays secure while working from home? </div>

      <span class="to-answertext">You can protect PHI by:</span> 
  <ul>
    <li>Accessing the COH network from home -- Always connect through our virtual private network (VPN) when accessing COH programs and data, and be mindful of your surroundings and who can see your screen.</li>
    <li>Storing electronic (ePHI) -- Store all ePHI on the COH network server, and never on your computer, flash drive or mobile device, unless in strict accordance with COH policies and procedures. If ePHI must be transported (USB, external hard drive, etc.) it must be encrypted.</li>
    <li>Storing printed PHI -- Do not maintain or transport physical copies of PHI while telecommuting unless this has been approved in advance in writing by your department director. Store all printed PHI in a secure place away from others, such as in a locked cabinet or drawer, and never on top of your desk or in your vehicle.</li> 
    <li>Disposing of PHI -- When documents are no longer needed to perform your job duties, promptly shred or return documents to their applicable storage location, following COH and department policies. For HIMS coders, shred the work list of assigned cases at the end of each workday.</li>
  </ul>
        <br/><span class="to-answertext">Please notify your supervisor and/or Annamarie Allison, City of Hope’s privacy manager, if you become aware of activities that violate our HIPAA policies.</span>

        <div class="to-question">How do I protect myself from a phishing email (e.g. a fraudulent email to obtain personal information, including patient PHI)? </div>

        <span class="to-answertext">It is important to be wary of opening messages and attachments and following hyperlinks from unknown sources. Always hover your mouse over hyperlinks to see where they are leading before you click. Be on the lookout for:</span>

        <ul><li>Messages from unsolicited sources -- The CDC shared <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2019/s0322-phishing.html" target="_blank">this example</a> from someone claiming to be the agency offering urgent tips to prevent the flu. When clicked, malware is installed on your computer, which encrypts and locks your files in exchange for payment.</li>
            <li>Emails, texts and phones calls from people you don’t know -- The Federal Communications Commission shared <a href="https://www.fcc.gov/covid-scams" target="_blank">this example</a> about messages offering COVID-19 testing kits, encouraging people to stock up on supplies, promoting cures, selling health insurance or asking for your personal information.</li>
        </ul>
        <span class="to-answertext">   If you think you’ve been phished, <a href="{!v.followsteps}" target="_blank">please follow these steps</a> or click the “Report Phishing” icon in Outlook. If you have questions about a message you received, please email our cyber security team at <a href="mailto:spam@coh.org" target="_blank">spam@coh.org.</a></span>

